Q: Why is my AWS bill high even after deleting AMIs?
A: Because snapshot created during AMI creation are still stored and charged seperately.

Note: If you mount a volume manually and restart the instance, the mount disappears unless we add entry in /etc/fstab
Scenario: You have an EC2 instance with a root or data volume . You increase the EBS volume size in AWS 
Original 20 GB
Increased: 40 GB
Now if we check inside linux
df -h you still see 20 GB not 40 GB why this happens?
AWS EBS volume is just a block device . Incresing the size updates virtual disk in AWS but Linux does not automatically resize filesystem on 
disk. the filesystem must be extended manually. 
first: verify new disk size lsblk -f
second: use linux command to extend filesystem on disk
if filesystem is ext4
then use command 
sudo resize2fs /dev/xvda1

if filesystem is xfs then use
sudo xfs_growfs /dev/xvda1

verify df -h
















  
